SIMPLE: neutralize
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Neutralize
<hw>Neu"tral*ize</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp.
& p. p.</pos> <conjf>Neutralized</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb.
n.</pos> <conjf>Neutralizing</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>.]</vmorph> <ety>[Cf.
F. <ets>neutraliser</ets>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To render neutral; to
reduce to a state of neutrality.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>So here I am <qex>neutralized</qex> again.</q> <rj><qau>Sir W.
Scott.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Chem.)</fld> <def>To render inert or imperceptible
the peculiar affinities of, as a chemical substance; to destroy the
effect of; <as>as, to <ex>neutralize</ex> an acid with a
base</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To destroy the peculiar properties or opposite
dispositions of; to reduce to a state of indifference or inefficiency;
to counteract; to render ineffective; <as>as, to <ex>neutralize</ex>
parties in government; to <ex>neutralize</ex> efforts, opposition,
etc.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Counter citations that <qex>neutralize</qex> each other.</q>
<rj><qau>E. Everett.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Neutralizer</ent>⟦br⟧
